  "prompt": "Do snakes really take revenge?",
  "response": "Snakes do not take revenge in the way humans understand it. They lack complex emotional processing and do not hold grudges or seek intentional retribution. Snake behavior is primarily driven by instinct, survival needs, and defensive responses. If a snake appears to be attacking repeatedly, it is more likely responding to:\n\n1. Feeling threatened\n2. Protecting its territory\n3. Perceiving something as a potential predator\n4. Defending itself when it feels cornered\n\nSnakes react to stimuli based on immediate survival instincts, not emotional motivations like revenge. Their actions are purely about self-preservation and responding to perceived threats.",
